<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
29. 
<taxonomicName LSID="7FD41F48-D05C-50C0-AE35-3516B8281219" authority="Peter, Nat. Pflanzenfam. [Engler &amp; Prantl] 4 (3 a): 36. 1891. (Peter 1891: 36)." authorityName="Peter, Nat. Pflanzenfam. [Engler &amp; Prantl] 4 (3 a): 36. 1891. (Peter" authorityYear="1891" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus boedeckerianus" order="Solanales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="boedeckerianus">Convolvulus boedeckerianus Peter, Nat. Pflanzenfam. [Engler &amp; Prantl] 4(3a): 36. 1891. (Peter 1891: 36).</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="type">
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
SOUTH AFRICA, Free State, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Boedecker</emphasis>
s.n. (lectotype GOET-002454, designated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Meeuse, ADL" journalOrPublisher="Flora of Southern Africa" pageId="207" pageNumber="208" pagination="1 - 138" refId="B226" refString="Meeuse, ADL, Welman, WG, 2000. Convolvulaceae. Flora of Southern Africa volume 28 (part 1): 1 - 138" title="Convolvulaceae." volume="volume 28" year="2000">Meeuse and Welman 2000</bibRefCitation>
: 40).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
Perennial herb with woody taproot from which spread numerous stems to 60 cm, plant covered in adpressed brown to silvery hairs. Leaves 1-2.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-2 cm, lanceolate to ovate in outline, variable in form from pinnatisect to palmately 5-lobed, often with the terminal lobe much longer and deeply toothed and the basal lobes bifid, base truncate to shallowly cordate; petioles 1-5 mm long. Flowers solitary, axillary, pedicellate but not pedunculate (rarely peduncle to 1mm); bracteoles 1-2 mm long, subulate; pedicels 2-6(-10) mm, outer sepals 4-5(-6) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-3 mm, ovate to oblong-elliptic, acute; corolla 7-10 mm long, pink or white, shallowly lobed, midpetaline bands pubescent with brown hairs; ovary glabrous; style glabrous, divided 2.5 mm above base; stigmas 2.5 mm, slightly widened upwards. Capsule glabrous; seeds glabrous, smooth but muricate on angles. [
<bibRefCitation author="Meeuse, ADL" journalOrPublisher="Bothalia" pageId="207" pageNumber="208" pagination="641 - 792" refId="B225" refString="Meeuse, ADL, 1958 1957. The South African Convolvulaceae. Bothalia 6: 641 - 792" title="The South African Convolvulaceae." volume="6" year="1958">Meeuse 1958</bibRefCitation>
: 674; 
<bibRefCitation author="Meeuse, ADL" journalOrPublisher="Flora of Southern Africa" pageId="207" pageNumber="208" pagination="1 - 138" refId="B226" refString="Meeuse, ADL, Welman, WG, 2000. Convolvulaceae. Flora of Southern Africa volume 28 (part 1): 1 - 138" title="Convolvulaceae." volume="volume 28" year="2000">Meeuse and Welman 2000</bibRefCitation>
: 40 (map)]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
South Africa except KwaZulu-Natal (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Prosser</emphasis>
1529, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Werger</emphasis>
289, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Shaw</emphasis>
123, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Brierley</emphasis>
173, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Flanagan</emphasis>
2112, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Duparquet</emphasis>
107).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="72" lastPageNumber="73" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
Distinguished by the solitary, pedicellate flowers and near absence of peduncles combined with the very small calyx, the sepals usually about 5 mm long and thinly covered in brownish hairs. The inflorescence is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hook., Bot. Mag. 70: t. 4065. 1844. (Hooker" authorityYear="1844" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus ocellatus" order="Solanales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ocellatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Convolvulus ocellatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but in that species the calyx is&gt;6 mm long and the whole plant is densely tomentose. It can be confused with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thunb., Prodr. Pl. Cap. 35. 1794. (Thunberg" authorityYear="1794" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus multifidus" order="Solanales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="multifidus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Convolvulus multifidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thunb., Prodr. Pl. Cap. 35. 1794. (Thunberg" authorityYear="1794" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus multifidus" order="Solanales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="multifidus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Convolvulus multifidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the calyx is larger. It could also be confused with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus austroafricanus" order="Solanales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Convolvulus austroafricanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but that species usually has several flowers which are always borne on a peduncle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<pageBreakToken pageId="72" pageNumber="73" start="start">There</pageBreakToken>
are specimens apparently intermediate with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus austroafricanus" order="Solanales" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Convolvulus austroafricanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
including 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Moss</emphasis>
4718 from Belmont, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Goosseno</emphasis>
728 from Free State and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Eyres</emphasis>
1820 and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Jacobsen</emphasis>
1772 from Zimbabwe. These have short but very distinct peduncles 5-10 mm long which bear 1-2 flowers, similar in dimensions to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peter, Nat. Pflanzenfam. [Engler &amp; Prantl] 4 (3 a): 36. 1891. (Peter" authorityYear="1891" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus boedeckerianus" order="Solanales" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="boedeckerianus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Convolvulus boedeckerianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Unlike 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus austroafricanus" order="Solanales" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Convolvulus austroafricanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
these plants are not very hirsute. Given the increasing evidence for hybridisation within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 153. 1753. (Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus" order="Solanales" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Convolvulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
these specimens may represent plants of hybrid origin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
